I seem to have a thing for bunnies. These are older paintings but Now that I have your attention did you know that rescue rabbits make adorable temporary holiday guests? The @houserabbitsociety with chapters across the US, is currently overflowing with rescues and looking for temporary fosters for a couple of weeks. The shelter provides the needed supplies, food, hay, toys and even the enclosures. Contrary to popular belief, rabbits are very social creatures, with a wide range of personalities and can be as affectionate as a dog or a cat. 🐇🐇
#houserabbitsociety

Omg, sort of embarrassing but funny. I was looking for postage stamps and found this. Back in the day before Instagram, artists used to have to send out physical promotions of their Art. This would have to be early 90s. I was trying to get freelance work so I made these little fold out accordion promo cards for myself. I’m cringing inside about the card but they’re still kind of cute. I would send them out in these translucent little envelopes. The image of the ambulance drivers is still one of my all-time favorites, and was the first piece of original art I ever sold and it was to a friend. I didn’t believe I could sell a Painting and I think he did it to convince me that I could. I Will always grateful for that kind gesture.

My grandma was A seamstress much of her life so consequently I got some really over the top frilly homemade dresses made for a few of my birthdays. We couldn’t afford much but damn if I wasn’t the most overdressed kid on picture day. I was allowed to wear them to school for special occasions and only if I wore shorts underneath so not to scandalize the playground while on the monkey bars. I still had to wear my regular shoes and not my church shoes which I realize now but didn’t then, were hiking boots. My friend called them waffle stompers😄

#purpletartan

This is for my daughter Raven. On April 21st she will undergo ACDF surgery to alleviate years of debilitating pain and weakness and tremors in her left hand that, despite physical therapy and non invasive treatments, has only grown worse impacting her ability to live a normal and productive life. At 34 she is on her way to a promising career in the medical field, where she needs two steady hands. We hope this surgery will restore full mobility and mostly, that she be pain free. This surgery involves opening the neck from the front, pushing the esophagus, carotid and jugular arteries to the side, shaving the bone that is crushing the nerves, and removing 3 discs from her spine that are compressing her spinal cord. The discs will be replaced with either cadaver bone or metal spacers, leaving her in a cervical collar for a months-long healing process that will leave her unable to work.
Once she recovers from her surgery she won’t be able to return to work full time and although she'll be mobile, the fusion takes at least one full year to take hold so she will still be too fragile to perform her very physical job. She has to take a long leave of absence at a job she loves and even with health insurance and what little the family are able to contribute, finances still pose a looming burden. Raven will move to a smaller place when her lease is up and is taking other steps to reduce her costs. 
Raven is a person who has always stepped in to help others. She's frequently volunteered in food kitchens during the holidays or raising funds for friends during their own medical emergencies. Now she is the one who needs help and it's hard as her mom to have to write this as I am not in a position to solve this problem for her.
I'm very proud of my girl having gotten to where she is on her own to become an incredible, tenacious young woman. She does have a challenging journey ahead of her and we want to relieve her financial burden so she can focus on her recovery.
If you are inclined, check out the fund raiser (my b i o)her friends set up for her. It explains what ACDF surgery is and why she needs it. (Raven with her two doggos, Bagels and Kelly.)
Super slow progress.

Heya friends and family, I want to thank you for the encouraging words and generous contributions to Raven's fundraiser. Some were anonymous and since I'm not running it, I don't know who you are but I thank you! As a small token of appreciation, If you gave, and would like an open edition print of the image below (still deciding the size), pm me your mailing address. It will be a few weeks before I can send anything. They will be art prints on Hahnemuhle rag paper. I made this painting a few years ago titled "Henbane and Nightshade" and chose the image because a friend once said about it, "she is determined despite it all". Not sure I quoted her precisely but it's fitting.

The “before” mood sporting an ultra spaceage puffy warm air blanket, here with her amazing BF. 3-4 more hours and she’ll be in recovery. Thanks to those who have commented and PM’d asking for an update. 💕#acdf and gratitude for the kind words and/or contributions 🌺

For everyone who asked for an update, here is the “after” pic. (I 100% have her blessing to share this awful photo!) surgery went very well. Raven is in a lot pain. Intermittent joking with the medical staff, and crying. going to take some time to heal but she’ll get there.❤️‍🩹#acdf 
thanks for all your kindness everyone!

We pimped Raven’s ride yesterday! She’s got an irrepressible attitude, despite it all. On our way to Portland we heard the terrible news that the very talented artist and co owner of Antler and Talon Galleries, Susannah Kelly @susannahkelly had passed away unexpectedly. I’m stunned and heartbroken for her husband and partner Neil Perry and their families. I had the chance to meet Susannah years ago when they gave me one the few solo shows I’ve had. She left a lasting impression on me of being whip smart, funny, kind and incredibly talented. They both worked incredibly hard to run the galleries and also make Art! Rest in Peace Susannah.

At the opening I was asked about this drawing. I don’t really think about what something is as I’m working but looking at it now, I think: more than a few times I’ve been referred to as “creepy” not with the kindest intentions (obvs!). People tend to be  uncomfortable around quiet folks like me. At the time I was also listening (again) to TED Klein’s “The Ceremonies”. It’s heavily atmospheric - strange happenings on a farm and creepiness in the nearby woods. I see myself as the creeper in the woods just sort basking in my weirdness. Turning it around, owning it.
Sort of a love note to all the other natural awkward peeps.
Thanks for everything @undergroundrobin and all the folks at @brassworksgallery.
